Base quality

Read length

Read mapping quality

Bases of each kind of CIGAR? status

CIGAR(Compact Idiosyncratic Gapped Alignment Report) is reported by aligner,
  • M: alignment match
  • I: insertion
  • D: deletion
  • N: skipped region
  • S: soft clipping
  • H: hard clipping
  • P: padding
  • =: sequence match
  • X: sequence mismatch
  • B: backwards skip

Bisulfite conversion

Conversion rate

  • 99.02%: from unmethylated control DNA (usually lambda DNA, 24,182 cytosines);
  • 99.02%: from mitochondrial DNA? (7,350 cytosines);
  • 99.01%: from nuclear CHHs? (86,264,555 sampled cytosines);
    • These estimates are available only for samples that MT DNA/nuclear CHHs are of no/little methylation.

Adjust DNAme level

DNAme level bias, i.e., observed DNAme level - real DNAme level, is dependent on (observed/unadjusted) DNAme level and bisulfite conversion rate. The theoretical relationsip is illustrated by the following figure. The dashed line indicates the estimated conversion rate in this sample.

Adjust (whole-genome) DNAme level according to incomplete bisulfite conversion. ? The conversion rate of 99.02% is adopted.

Over-conversion is inestimable in usual samples and not modeled in bsDoctor.

  • CGs (depth ≥ 1): observed: 47.34%, adjusted: 46.81%;
  • CHGs (depth ≥ 1): observed: 1.089%, adjusted: 0.1052%;
  • CHHs (depth ≥ 1): observed: 1.044%, adjusted: 0.05971%.

Base-level error

The base-level error, assuming the reads are mapped to correct genomic positions, is estimated by the proportion of inconsistent bases, namely ?

Only available when mutation rate is much less than error rate.
$$ \text {error rate} = \frac {\text {\#\{bases different with dominating base\} } } { \#\text{\{total mapped bases\} } }. $$

  • For nuclear genome, from bases mapped to A/T sites?: 0.7384%;
    • Most single-nucleotide variations (SNVs) are C → T and G → A.
  • For mitochondrial genome: 7.004%
  • For spike-in unmethylated control DNA: 15.55%

DNA template loss

The part of (nuclear) DNA that degraded during library construction and the part of undegraded but not sequenced DNA can be estimated with empirical Bayes model?.

Refer to Efron and Hastie (2016) Chapter 6 for more information of empirical Bayes model.
  • sequenced (depth ≥ 1): 90.26%
  • undegraded but not sequenced: 0.1538%
  • degenerated: 9.587% ?
    • DNA template loss is due to degradation (library quality) or selection (for example RRBS protocol).
  • ultimate coverage (by sequencing continuously): 90.26% + 0.1538% = 90.41%
  • saturation: 99.85%

DNA copy number

Mitochondrion DNA copy number is estimated by the average depth of MTs over that of nuclear chromosomes. ? $$ \text{MT DNA copy number} = \frac{ \text{mean read depth of MT DNA} } { \text{mean read depth of nuclear DNA} } = \frac{ 45947.0 }{ 42.3 } \times 2 (\text{ploidy}) = 2,173 $$

The estimate is less accurate for RRBS samples than WGBS samples due to selective enrichment of DNA fragments.
Change the coefficient accordingly if not diploidy.

Bisulfite conversion

From the 'methylation' of cytosines in MT genome ?, we can estimate bisulfite conversion rate as $$ \text{conversion rate} = 1-\text{MT methylation level} = 1 - 0.009798 = 99.02\%. $$

Assume MT DNA is not (5mC) methylated.

Error rate

The (base-level) error rate that a base is mis-detected during library preparation, sequencing, and alignment, can be estimated ? from inconsistent bases mapped to MT genome. From the error rate distribution of 20-bp binning windows, the average error rate is $$ \text{error rate} = \frac{\text{bases different with dominating base}}{\text{total read bases}} = 7.004 \%. $$

Mutation rate is usually smaller than error rate in bisulfite-seq samples.

Unmethylated control DNA

  • 48,502 bps in total, whereas 100% are covered (48,502 bps for depth ≥ 1);
  • 24,182 cytosines in total, whereas 100% are covered (24,182 cytosines for depth ≥ 1).

Read depth

  • Binnng size: 50 bp
  • Read depth: 5947(mean), 3685(median)

Check the uniformness of coverage depth

Bisulfite conversion

From the 'methylation' of cytosines in control DNA, we can estimate bisulfite conversion rate ? as $$ \text{conversion rate} = 1-\text{control DNA methylation level} = 99.02\%. $$

The actual estimate of 'methylation level' is the median of methylation of each bin which is robust.

Error rate

The error rate that a base is mis-detected during library preparation, sequencing, and alignment, can be estimated from inconsistent bases mapped to control DNA. From the error rate distribution of 50-bp bins, the average error rate ? is $$ \text{error rate} = \frac{\text{bases different with dominating base}}{\text{total bases}} = 15.55\%. $$

The actual error rate estimate is the median of each bin which is robust.

CpGs of double-stranded coverage

Proportion of double-stranded covered CpGs at different depths. $$ \text{proportion of CpGs of double-stranded coverage} = \frac{\#\{ \text{CpGs with Watson and Crick depths both} \ge \text{DP}\}} {\#\{ \text{CpGs with either Watson or Crick depths} \ge \text{DP}\}} $$

RRBS motif

Reduced Representation Bisulfite Sequencing (RRBS) uses a methylation-insensitive restriction enzyme, usually MspI with the cutting target 5'C^CGG3' sequences (^ is the cutting site), to enrich CpGs. The enrichment undoubtedly causes preference/bias.

  • lefttop: Proportion of CCGG-context CpGs over all CpGs in the genome is 7.905%
  • leftbottom: Mean single-stranded methylation read depth of CCGG-context CpGs is 11.46
  • righttop: Coverage rate of CCGG- and non-CCGG-context CpGs with varing depth thresholds
  • rightbottom: Mean methyaltion level of CCGG- and non-CCGG-context CpGs with varing depth thresholds
This result is also meaningful for non-RRBS samples.
